        '[Opening Hook] → [Setup Summary] → [Initial Context] → [Turning Point] → [Strategic Pivot] → [Challenge Introduction] → [Results] → [Final Outcome] → [Lessons Learned]',
        '[Opening Hook - 1 line, 10-12 words] Introduce the company that was dismissed but succeeded.',
        '[Setup Summary - 2 lines, 25-30 words] Brief overview of near-bankruptcy and pivot moment. [Initial Context - 1 line + 3 bullet points] Challenges faced at low point. [Turning Point - 1 line] The moment they changed direction. [Strategic Pivot - 2 lines] What they bet on and when. [Challenge Introduction - 2 lines] Early obstacles to the new direction. [Results - 3 bullet points] Measurable growth and success metrics. [Final Outcome - 2 lines] Ultimate impact on the industry. [Lessons Learned - 1 line + 3 bullet points] Key principles for industry redefinition.',
        'How to redefine an industry: Bet early on inevitable shifts. Embrace your own obsolescence. Build for behavior, not legacy.',
        ARRAY['Near-failure story', 'Industry pivot', 'Category-defining', 'Timing lessons', 'Adaptation focus', 'Consumer behavior', 'Dates and data', 'Smooth transitions', 'Cinematic pacing', 'Bold inflection points'],
        E'The company Blockbuster laughed at just changed entertainment forever:\n\nNetflix was nearly bankrupt in 2001. But a single pivot — betting on streaming before the world was ready — changed everything.\n\nHere''s what Netflix faced back then:\n• Declining DVD rentals\n• Mounting shipping costs\n• Rejected acquisition by Blockbuster ($50M offer turned down)\n\nThey stopped mailing DVDs — and started building a future.\n\nBy 2007, Netflix quietly launched streaming, betting on broadband adoption ahead of its time.\n\nThe tech was clunky, licenses scarce, and critics brutal. But consumers adapted faster than expected.\n\nResults:\n• Subscriber base grew from 7M to 60M in 3 years\n• Stock up 900%\n• Streaming revenue surpassed DVDs by 2010\n\nBy 2025, Netflix had reshaped global media — and created the binge economy.\n\nHow to redefine an industry:\n• Bet early on inevitable shifts.\n• Embrace your own obsolescence.\n• Build for behavior, not legacy.'
