-- Repurpose / NewsJacking Templates (5 templates)
    (
        'Repurpose / NewsJacking',
        'The ''Secret Weapon'' Playbook',
        'Detail the story of a key person who turned a crisis into a major success. Break down their specific framework and principles so others can learn from their legendary comeback.',
        E'Opening Hook → Context Setting → Strategic Concession → Counter-Premise → Transition → Point 1 (Rebrand purpose) → Point 2 (Emotion first) → Point 3 (Sell belonging) → Final Lesson',
        E'Opening Hook - 10–15 words: Start with bold admiration + result contrast\nContext Setting - 20–25 words: Summarize situation, crisis, and pivot point\nStrategic Concession - 15–20 words: Acknowledge real struggle or context\nCounter-Premise - 20–25 words: Show contrast between obvious reason and true reason\nTransition - 3–5 words',
        E'Point 1 Structure:\nHeader — "1. Rebrand the purpose, not the product"\nPrimary Fact — Show identity shift over product pitch\nSupporting Detail — Explain cultural alignment\n\nPoint 2 Structure:\nHeader — "2. Lead with emotion, follow with execution"\nReality Check — Faith before results\nImpact — Brand revival timeline\n\nPoint 3 Structure:\nHeader — "3. Sell belonging, not features"\nEvidence — Community creation strategy\nCriticism — What competitors miss\n\nFinal Lesson - 10–15 words',
        E'End with memorable truth about purpose vs. product',
        ARRAY['quotes and slogans for punch', 'mix storytelling with facts', 'short paragraphs (2-3 lines max)', 'italics for emotional cues', 'bold admiration tone', 'result contrast', 'crisis narrative', 'psychological insight', 'brand revival focus', 'emotion over features', 'purpose-driven', 'cultural alignment'],
        E'The comeback that saved Apple wasn''t built on tech — it was built on psychology:\n\nIn 1997, Apple was 90 days from bankruptcy. Steve Jobs'' ''Think Different'' campaign didn''t sell computers — it sold belief.\n\nYes, Apple made great products. But products alone don''t rebuild a culture.\n\nEveryone credits iMac for the comeback — but it started with one campaign that redefined how the world felt about Apple.\n\nHere''s how it worked:\n\n1. Rebrand the purpose, not the product\n\n''Think Different'' told users who they were, not what to buy.\n\nIt aligned identity with creativity — Apple became the tool for rebels.\n\n2. Lead with emotion, follow with execution\n\nThe ads dropped before the new iMac even shipped — faith came first.\n\nBrand revival began before revenue recovery.\n\n3. Sell belonging, not features\n\n''Crazy Ones'' ad created a tribe long before ''community'' became a buzzword.\n\nThat''s what most companies still don''t get — emotion scales faster than hardware.\n\nYour product can be copied. Your purpose can''t.'
    ),
    (
        'Repurpose / NewsJacking',
        'The Underdog''s Playbook',
        'Structure the complete journey of a founder or product, from idea to breakthrough. Highlight early doubts, competition, and the principles that flipped their disadvantage into strength.',
        E'Opening Hook → Context Setting → Strategic Concession → Counter-Premise → Transition → Point 1 (Play niche) → Point 2 (Turn constraints) → Point 3 (Make noise) → Final Lesson',
        E'Opening Hook - 10–15 words: Bold claim about underdog success\nContext Setting - 20–25 words: Show humble beginnings\nStrategic Concession - 15–20 words: Acknowledge they weren''t exceptional\nCounter-Premise - 20–25 words: Reframe weakness as advantage\nTransition - 3–5 words',
        E'Point 1 Structure:\nHeader — "1. Play where giants won''t"\nPrimary Fact — Niche strategy\nSupporting Detail — Market positioning\n\nPoint 2 Structure:\nHeader — "2. Turn constraints into creativity"\nReality Check — Budget limitations as catalyst\nImpact — Leverage from limitation\n\nPoint 3 Structure:\nHeader — "3. Make noise, not noise complaints"\nEvidence — Controversy as marketing\nCriticism — Rebellion strategy\n\nFinal Lesson - 10–15 words',
        E'End with "mic-drop" truth line about outlasting competitors',
        ARRAY['narrative beats like movie script', 'short sharp rhythm', 'mic-drop truth line', 'underdog narrative', 'competitive advantage framing', 'niche focus', 'constraint-based creativity', 'controversy marketing', 'scrappy tone', 'rebellion positioning', 'persistence theme', 'leverage thinking'],
        E'The startup everyone laughed at just outperformed billion-dollar giants:\n\nTwo founders. No funding. No network. But what they had — no one could compete with.\n\nThey weren''t the smartest or richest — they were just too stubborn to quit.\n\nPeople mistake underdogs for weak — but being underestimated is the greatest competitive advantage there is.\n\nHere''s how they flipped it:\n\n1. Play where giants won''t\n\nThey built in a niche everyone ignored — freelancers.\n\nWhile big players chased enterprises, they dominated individuals.\n\n2. Turn constraints into creativity\n\nNo marketing budget? They made their customers do it for them.\n\nEvery limitation became leverage.\n\n3. Make noise, not noise complaints\n\nThey owned controversy. Every backlash brought more attention.\n\nSometimes rebellion is the marketing plan.\n\nIf you can''t outspend, outsmart. If you can''t outsmart, outlast.'
    ),
    (
        'Repurpose / NewsJacking',
        'Look to the Past to See the Future',
        'Use a historical parallel to analyze a modern shift. Show how similar dynamics played out before — and what lessons today''s companies or creators can learn.',
        E'Opening Hook → Context Setting → Strategic Concession → Counter-Premise → Transition → Point 1 (Hype cycle) → Point 2 (Platform evolution) → Point 3 (Distribution control) → Final Lesson',
        E'Opening Hook - 10–15 words: History rhymes statement\nContext Setting - 20–25 words: Connect current event to historical parallel\nStrategic Concession - 15–20 words: Acknowledge novelty\nCounter-Premise - 20–25 words: Reveal the pattern\nTransition - 3–5 words',
        E'Point 1 Structure:\nHeader — "1. The hype cycle always starts the same"\nPrimary Fact — Historical examples of similar hype\nSupporting Detail — Pattern of rediscovery\n\nPoint 2 Structure:\nHeader — "2. Platforms don''t die — they evolve"\nReality Check — Evolution examples\nImpact — Core formula consistency\n\nPoint 3 Structure:\nHeader — "3. The winners always control distribution"\nEvidence — Distribution over innovation\nCriticism — Platform advantage truth\n\nFinal Lesson - 10–15 words',
        E'End with reflective insight about patterns vs. platforms',
        ARRAY['compare old vs new with bold contrasts', 'nostalgia + insight tone', 'examples from 2-3 eras', 'reflective ending', 'historical parallel', 'pattern recognition', 'tech cycles', 'platform analysis', 'evolution narrative', 'distribution focus', 'cynical wisdom', 'meta-analysis'],
        E'History doesn''t repeat — but it rhymes. Especially in tech:\n\nEveryone''s freaking out about [New Feature]. But if you''ve seen the rise of [Old Platform], you already know where this ends.\n\nYes, it''s new tech. But the same story plays out every decade — ego vs evolution.\n\nThe real pattern isn''t innovation — it''s imitation wrapped in better UX.\n\nHere''s the parallel:\n\n1. The hype cycle always starts the same\n\n''This will change everything!'' — just like we said about Vine, Clubhouse, and Threads.\n\nEvery generation rediscovers virality like it''s new.\n\n2. Platforms don''t die — they evolve\n\nFacebook became Meta. Twitter became X. Change is rebranding, not rebirth.\n\nThe core formula stays — attention, content, monetization.\n\n3. The winners always control distribution\n\nYou don''t need innovation if you own the audience pipeline.\n\nThat''s why history always favors the platforms, not the creators.\n\nStudy patterns, not platforms. The future hides in repetition.'
    ),
    (
        'Repurpose / NewsJacking',
        'What''s Flashy vs. What Actually Works',
        'Debunk a popular trend by exposing its flaws. Contrast a flashy, viral example with a boring but effective one. Show your audience why substance beats style.',
        E'Opening Hook → Context Setting → Strategic Concession → Counter-Premise → Transition → Point 1 (Flashy = churn) → Point 2 (Utility compounds) → Point 3 (Systems win) → Final Lesson',
        E'Opening Hook - 10–15 words: Call out trend obsession\nContext Setting - 20–25 words: Simplicity over complexity message\nStrategic Concession - 15–20 words: Acknowledge appeal\nCounter-Premise - 20–25 words: Boring beats sexy truth\nTransition - 3–5 words',
        E'Point 1 Structure:\nHeader — "1. Flashy = high churn"\nPrimary Fact — Stat about viral tool retention\nSupporting Detail — Novelty vs reliability\n\nPoint 2 Structure:\nHeader — "2. Utility compounds"\nReality Check — Integration efficiency\nImpact — Simplification principle\n\nPoint 3 Structure:\nHeader — "3. Systems win long-term"\nEvidence — Lasting tool example\nCriticism — Trend fade reality\n\nFinal Lesson - 10–15 words',
        E'End with memorable one-liner about function vs. flash',
        ARRAY['real stats + product names', 'viral vs valuable contrast', 'sections under 3 lines', 'memorable one-liner ending', 'trend debunking', 'substance over style', 'efficiency focus', 'system thinking', 'retention data', 'simplification advocacy', 'pragmatic tone', 'anti-hype'],
        E'Everyone''s obsessed with the next shiny AI tool — and it''s killing their productivity:\n\nYou don''t need 12 Chrome extensions to be efficient. You need 1 system that actually works.\n\nYes, those flashy tools look fun. But dopamine ≠ discipline.\n\nThe truth: boring systems outperform sexy tools — because consistency always beats novelty.\n\nHere''s proof:\n\n1. Flashy = high churn\n\nMost viral AI tools lose 70% of users in 30 days (AppBrain 2024).\n\nNovelty spikes usage — reliability sustains it.\n\n2. Utility compounds\n\nOne well-integrated tool saves 5x the time of 10 new ones.\n\nStack less. Simplify more.\n\n3. Systems win long-term\n\nNotion didn''t trend — it lasted.\n\nBecause trends fade faster than workflows evolve.\n\nFlash gets attention. Function gets results.'
    ),
    (
        'Repurpose / NewsJacking',
        'Behind Every Great Leader (The System They Use)',
        'Break down how great leaders build and scale systems. Highlight processes behind talent, communication, and performance — showing that leadership is design, not charisma.',
        E'Opening Hook → Context Setting → Strategic Concession → Counter-Premise → Transition → Point 1 (Hire frameworks) → Point 2 (Build loops) → Point 3 (Optimize scale) → Final Lesson',
        E'Opening Hook - 10–15 words: Systems over mindset claim\nContext Setting - 20–25 words: Leader examples and their real edge\nStrategic Concession - 15–20 words: Acknowledge vision\nCounter-Premise - 20–25 words: Design over doing more\nTransition - 3–5 words',
        E'Point 1 Structure:\nHeader — "1. Hire for frameworks, not resumes"\nPrimary Fact — Recruiter strategy\nSupporting Detail — Frameworks vs output\n\nPoint 2 Structure:\nHeader — "2. Build decision loops"\nReality Check — Feedback systems\nImpact — Culture as manager\n\nPoint 3 Structure:\nHeader — "3. Optimize for scale, not speed"\nEvidence — Systems vs battles\nCriticism — Scaled chaos warning\n\nFinal Lesson - 10–15 words',
        E'End with practical truth about repeatable leadership',
        ARRAY['verbs like design build optimize', 'analytical not emotional tone', 'practical truth ending', 'leadership examples for authority', 'system design focus', 'process over charisma', 'scalability emphasis', 'framework thinking', 'feedback loops', 'culture design', 'anti-chaos', 'repeatable methods'],
        E'The secret behind elite leaders isn''t mindset — it''s systems:\n\nFrom Musk to Nadella, their real edge isn''t motivation speeches. It''s scalable process loops built into culture.\n\nYes, they''re visionary. But vision without structure is just chaos in fancy clothes.\n\nLeadership isn''t about doing more — it''s about designing systems that let others do more without you.\n\nHere''s the blueprint:\n\n1. Hire for frameworks, not resumes\n\nGreat leaders recruit thinkers who can design repeatable solutions.\n\nResumes show output. Frameworks show thought process.\n\n2. Build decision loops\n\nThey create feedback systems that auto-correct without micromanagement.\n\nCulture becomes the manager.\n\n3. Optimize for scale, not speed\n\nSpeed wins battles. Systems win wars.\n\nEvery ''visionary'' who fails usually just scaled chaos.\n\nLeadership isn''t loud. It''s repeatable.'
