-- How Tos Templates (5 templates)
    (
        'How Tos',
        'The Expert''s Diagnostic Checklist',
        'Present a systematic checklist to diagnose the root cause of any problem. Guide your audience away from ineffective fixes and toward a structured, expert-level analysis.',
        E'Opening Challenge → Problem Statement → Common Misconception → Value Proposition → Expertise Introduction → Framework Structure (4 steps: Initial Analysis, Key Metrics, Problem Identification, Solution Framework) → Closing Statement',
        E'Opening Challenge Section - 2–3 lines: [Role]: "[Common complaint]" / Me: [Expert response]\nProblem Statement - 1–2 lines\nCommon Misconception - 1–2 lines\nValue Proposition - 1–2 lines\nExpertise Introduction - 1–2 lines',
        E'Framework Structure:\n\n1 – Initial Analysis\n• Work backward from the problem\n• Identify what''s broken (people, process, or tool)\n• Define success metrics\n• Clarify accountability\n\n2 – Key Metrics\nTrack these first:\n• [Industry metric 1]\n• [Industry metric 2]\n• [Industry metric 3]\n• [Industry metric 4]\n• [Industry metric 5]\n\n3 – Problem Identification\nFind the common root causes:\n• Root cause 1\n• Root cause 2\n• Root cause 3\n• Root cause 4\n• Root cause 5\n• Root cause 6\n\n4 – Solution Framework\nApply targeted fixes:\n• Solution approach 1\n• Solution approach 2\n• Solution approach 3\n• Solution approach 4\n\nClosing Statement - 2 lines',
        E'End with reflective truth about root cause vs. surface fix',
        ARRAY['bullets for lists', 'line breaks between sections', '1-2 lines per paragraph', 'numbers for order', 'action verbs prominent', 'systematic checklist', 'diagnostic framework', 'expert positioning', 'metrics-driven', 'root cause analysis', 'structured problem-solving', 'industry KPIs'],
        E'GTM Leader: "My SDR team isn''t performing."\nMe: Here''s my diagnostic checklist to figure out why.\n\nYour SDR team is missing quota and you don''t know where to start fixing it.\n\nMost GTM leaders jump straight to firing people or changing comp plans.\n\nBut you''re wasting time and money if you don''t diagnose the real problem first.\n\nHere''s my 4-step diagnostic checklist after working with 15+ SDR teams:\n\n1 – Initial Analysis\n• Work backward from the problem\n• Identify what''s broken (people, process, or tool)\n• Define success metrics\n• Clarify accountability\n\n2 – Key Metrics\nTrack these first:\n• Meetings booked per rep\n• SQL → close ratio\n• Lead response time (avg. minutes)\n• Pipeline coverage ratio (3–4x rule)\n• Demo → Opportunity conversion\n\n3 – Problem Identification\nFind the common root causes:\n• Low activity due to unclear ICP\n• Messaging mismatch\n• Poor CRM hygiene\n• Unrealistic targets\n• Misaligned incentives\n• Lack of enablement resources\n\n4 – Solution Framework\nApply targeted fixes:\n• Redefine ICP with revenue-backed data\n• Build an objection-handling doc\n• Train reps on storytelling, not scripts\n• Rebuild dashboards for visibility\n\nFiring someone is rarely the answer.\nIt''s usually the process that''s broken.'
    ),
    (
        'How Tos',
        'The Power of Saying No',
        'Explain the counterintuitive math of how doing less leads to more. Show how rejecting the wrong customers, channels, or products amplifies growth.',
        E'Opening Hook → 7 Numbered Principles (Guess and Test, Bullseye Method, Leverage Unfair Advantage, Build Around You, Get Specific, Go Narrower, Cut The Rest)',
        E'Opening Hook - 2 parts, 15–20 words: Shocking action + massive result + framework name',
        E'Each principle follows pattern:\n\nNumber) TITLE IN CAPS\n"Story with concrete example and metric."\n"Key insight or lesson."\n"Supporting detail or analogy."\n\nPrinciples:\n1) GUESS AND TEST - Pick one, test fast\n2) THE BULLSEYE METHOD - Identify BEST customer\n3) LEVERAGE YOUR UNFAIR ADVANTAGE - Play to strengths\n4) BUILD AROUND YOU - Strengths over trends\n5) GET SPECIFIC - Name, face, problem, solution\n6) GO NARROWER - Niche down further\n7) CUT THE REST - Show dramatic proof (metrics)',
        E'End with proof-driven takeaway contrasting focus vs scale',
        ARRAY['number each major point', 'emojis sparingly for impact', 'one-sentence paragraphs for rhythm', 'mix data with storytelling', 'shocking opener', 'real metrics', 'credibility through simplicity', 'proof-driven', 'counterintuitive positioning', 'niche focus', 'ICP specificity', 'contrarian advice'],
        E'I fired HALF our customers. Our profits 5X''d. The counterintuitive math of saying ''no'' to grow:\n\n1) GUESS AND TEST\n"At Kahani, we wasted time on tiny e-comm shops = 10% conversion.\nPivoted to brands with 100+ SKUs = 30% conversion.\nDon''t overthink. Pick one. Test fast."\n\n2) THE BULLSEYE METHOD\n"Identify your BEST customer — the one you''d say ''HELL YEAH'' to.\nThat''s your bullseye.\nAt GrowthAssistant, we dropped e-comm, focused on agencies — retention doubled."\n\n3) LEVERAGE YOUR UNFAIR ADVANTAGE\n"''Jesse, you only grew because of your Ampush experience!''\nDamn right. Your unfair advantage = your ICP advantage."\n\n4) BUILD AROUND YOU\n"In GA''s early days, I ran marketing/sales; Adriane nailed hiring.\nPlay to your strengths, not trends."\n\n5) GET SPECIFIC\n"Not ''small biz owners.''\nIt''s ''Nathan, 28, 7-figure agency, needs systems to scale.''\nName. Face. Problem. Solution."\n\n6) GO NARROWER\n"''Digital marketing for ORTHODONTISTS'' = massive business.\nEven when you think you''re niche, go narrower."\n\n7) CUT THE REST\n"At Ampush, we cut HALF our customers.\n📉 Growth: 75% ↓\n📈 Profit: 500% ↑\nFocus beats scale — every time."'
    ),
    (
        'How Tos',
        'The Playbook That Got Me Here',
        'Codify the lessons from a major achievement into a repeatable playbook. Break down tactics, frameworks, and before/after comparisons so others can follow your path.',
        E'Opening Hook → 5 Sections (Find the Gap, Test Your Signal, Systemize Success, Build Authority Loop, Scale Smarter) → Closing Lesson',
        E'Opening Hook - 2–3 lines: Major milestone + playbook promise',
        E'Section Structure (5 steps or fewer):\n\nSection X - TITLE IN CAPS\n• Bullet point 1 (actionable)\n• Bullet point 2 (actionable)\n• Bullet point 3 (actionable)\n\nSections:\n1 - FIND THE GAP\n• Identify complaints\n• Solve manually first\n• Measure pain frequency\n\n2 - TEST YOUR SIGNAL\n• Launch single offer\n• Customer interviews before scaling\n• Get paying users before automating\n\n3 - SYSTEMIZE SUCCESS\n• Document repeatable actions\n• Convert wins into SOPs\n• Automate time sinks\n\n4 - BUILD YOUR AUTHORITY LOOP\n• Post learnings publicly\n• Feedback → improve → post cycle\n• Compound visibility\n\n5 - SCALE SMARTER\n• Don''t hire unknown roles\n• Simplify before delegating\n• Weekly metrics check\n\nClosing Lesson - 2 lines: Truth about consistency',
        E'End with truth about repetition over reinvention',
        ARRAY['5 steps or fewer', 'one verb per section title', 'each bullet practical', 'past results as anchors', 'playbook format', 'repeatable framework', 'milestone credibility', 'systemization focus', 'authority building', 'scaling principles', 'SOP emphasis', 'weekly cadence'],
        E'Last year, I went from 0 → $250K ARR.\nHere''s the playbook that got me here — step by step:\n\nSection 1 - FIND THE GAP\n• Identify what everyone complains about\n• Solve that problem manually first\n• Measure pain point frequency (is it real or rare?)\n\nSection 2 - TEST YOUR SIGNAL\n• Launch with a single offer\n• Use 10 customer interviews before scaling\n• Get 3 paying users before you automate anything\n\nSection 3 - SYSTEMIZE SUCCESS\n• Document every repeatable action\n• Convert recurring wins into SOPs\n• Automate top 3 time sinks\n\nSection 4 - BUILD YOUR AUTHORITY LOOP\n• Post weekly learnings publicly\n• Collect feedback → improve product → post again\n• Compound visibility into authority\n\nSection 5 - SCALE SMARTER\n• Don''t hire for roles you don''t understand\n• Simplify before delegating\n• Reinforce with weekly metrics check\n\nThe biggest playbook isn''t the system — it''s consistency.\nYou win by repetition, not reinvention.'
    ),
    (
        'How Tos',
        'How One Sentence Can Change The Game',
        'Show how one powerful sentence — a phrase, mindset, or pitch — changed your results. Demonstrate the "before" vs. "after" transformation to highlight the power of clarity.',
        E'Opening Hook → Section 1 (Before State) → Section 2 (The Shift) → Section 3 (The Framework) → Section 4 (The Application) → Closing Line',
        E'Opening Hook - 2–3 lines: Not a tool/strategy, a sentence\nSection 1 - THE BEFORE STATE: Old sentence + poor result\nSection 2 - THE SHIFT: New sentence + dramatic result\nSection 3 - THE FRAMEWORK: 4-step process to find your sentence\nSection 4 - THE APPLICATION: Where to use it',
        E'Section 1 - THE BEFORE STATE\n• We used to say: "[vague positioning]"\n• Result: [negative outcome]\n\nSection 2 - THE SHIFT\n• We rewrote it as: "[specific, quantifiable positioning]"\n• Result: [positive outcome with metric]\n\nSection 3 - THE FRAMEWORK\nHere''s how to find your own:\n• Define your who (specific audience)\n• Quantify your outcome (measurable win)\n• Remove buzzwords (keep it human)\n• Test it in your bio or cold outreach\n\nSection 4 - THE APPLICATION\n• Add it to your headline\n• Put it in your pitch deck\n• Open every post with it\n\nClosing Line - 1–2 lines: Truth about clarity',
        E'End with crisp truth about message clarity and repeatability',
        ARRAY['contrast before vs after clearly', 'use quotes for sentences', 'short declarative bullets', 'crisp truth line ending', 'clarity emphasis', 'messaging framework', 'quantifiable positioning', 'buzzword removal', 'specificity focus', 'before/after proof', 'repeatability test', 'pitch optimization'],
        E'One sentence changed everything for us.\nNot a tool. Not a strategy. A sentence.\n\nSection 1 - THE BEFORE STATE\n• We used to say: "We help businesses grow."\n• Result: Nobody cared. Zero DMs. No trust.\n\nSection 2 - THE SHIFT\n• We rewrote it as: "We help B2B founders book 10+ sales calls/month with zero ads."\n• Result: Booked 14 inbound calls the same week.\n\nSection 3 - THE FRAMEWORK\nHere''s how to find your own:\n• Define your who (specific audience)\n• Quantify your outcome (measurable win)\n• Remove buzzwords (keep it human)\n• Test it in your bio or cold outreach\n\nSection 4 - THE APPLICATION\n• Add it to your headline\n• Put it in your pitch deck\n• Open every post with it\n\nOne clear sentence outperforms a 10-slide deck.\nIf people can''t repeat what you do, you don''t own your message.'
    ),
    (
        'How Tos',
        'The #1 Mistake Before A Big Win',
        'Reveal the single biggest mistake people make before reaching a major milestone. Then show your framework for avoiding it — guiding readers from "almost failed" to "finally won."',
        E'Opening Hook → Section 1 (The Mistake) → Section 2 (The Realization) → Section 3 (Framework to Fix) → Section 4 (The Win) → Section 5 (The Lesson)',
        E'Opening Hook - 2 lines: Everyone talks about winning, no one talks about the mistake\nSection 1 - THE MISTAKE: Specific error + consequence\nSection 2 - THE REALIZATION: Core insight (Growth ≠ Progress)\nSection 3 - THE FRAMEWORK TO FIX IT: 4 changes made\nSection 4 - THE WIN: Timeframe + metrics\nSection 5 - THE LESSON: Reflective truth',
        E'Section 1 - THE MISTAKE\n"[Specific mistake with context]"\n"[Consequence - nearly killed business/project]"\n\nSection 2 - THE REALIZATION\n"[Core truth uncovered]"\n"[Contrast: chasing X instead of Y]"\n\nSection 3 - THE FRAMEWORK TO FIX IT\n"Here''s what I changed:"\n• Change 1 (specific action)\n• Change 2 (specific action)\n• Change 3 (specific action)\n• Change 4 (specific action)\n\nSection 4 - THE WIN\n"[Timeframe] later — [metric 1], [metric 2], [metric 3]."\n\nSection 5 - THE LESSON\n"The mistake before the win is usually [pattern]."\n"[Final truth about focus/validation/scaling]."\n\nClosing: 2 lines max, reflective and teachable',
        E'End with teachable truth maintaining vulnerability-to-victory arc',
        ARRAY['clear story arc (Mistake → Realization → Fix → Win → Lesson)', 'each section under 3 lines', 'metrics prove turnaround', 'reflective teachable truth', 'emotional honesty', 'vulnerability before victory', 'real numbers and timeframes', 'framework clarity', 'almost-failed narrative', 'pivot story', 'validation emphasis', 'scaling principles'],
        E'Everyone talks about the moment they won.\nNo one talks about the mistake that almost stopped them.\n\nSection 1 - THE MISTAKE\n"I tried to scale before proving retention.\nIt nearly killed my business — 3 clients churned in a week."\n\nSection 2 - THE REALIZATION\n"Growth ≠ progress.\nI was chasing speed instead of repeatability."\n\nSection 3 - THE FRAMEWORK TO FIX IT\n"Here''s what I changed:"\n• Measured retention before scaling ads\n• Doubled client feedback loops\n• Added a 30-day "proof" period for all new offers\n• Removed any process we couldn''t repeat twice\n\nSection 4 - THE WIN\n"3 months later — 0 churn, 2x referrals, 4x MRR."\n\nSection 5 - THE LESSON\n"The mistake before the win is usually doing too much, too fast.\nFocus, validate, then scale."'
    ),
    
-- Personal Beliefs Templates (5 templates)
    (
        'Personal Beliefs',
        'The Right Advice At The Wrong Time',
        'Challenge a famous piece of advice in your industry. Explain why context matters and show how to test whether that advice fits your stage, model, or situation.',
        E'Opening Statement → Impact Description → Context Setting → Unexpected Turn → Initial Reaction → Transition to Core Story → Introduction to Key Points → Problem List → Reflection Bridge → Core Wisdom → Advice Introduction → Advice List → Emotional Response → Balanced Perspective → Universal Truth → Target Audience Call-Out → Call to Action → Reflection Questions → Final Guidance → Closing Statement',
        E'Opening Statement - Single line, personal action\nImpact Description - Two lines\nContext Setting - Two lines\nUnexpected Turn - Two lines\nInitial Reaction - Two lines\nTransition to Core Story - Two lines\nIntroduction to Key Points - One line',
        E'Problem List - 4-5 bullet points:\n• Problem 1\n• Problem 2\n• Problem 3\n• Problem 4\n• Problem 5 (optional)\n\nReflection Bridge - One to two lines\n\nCore Wisdom - Two lines\n\nAdvice Introduction - One line\n\nAdvice List - 4-5 bullet points:\n• Advice 1\n• Advice 2\n• Advice 3\n• Advice 4\n• Advice 5 (optional)\n\nEmotional Response - Two lines\n\nBalanced Perspective - Two lines\n\nUniversal Truth - Two to three lines\n\nTarget Audience Call-Out - One line\n\nCall to Action - Two lines\n\nReflection Questions - Two lines\n\nFinal Guidance - One line\n\nClosing Statement - One line',
        E'End with memorable truth about context and timing',
        ARRAY['single line breaks between sections', 'double line breaks before lists', 'short paragraphs (1-3 lines)', 'no hashtags', 'minimal emoji', 'triple line breaks for drama', 'context-dependent advice', 'stage awareness', 'personal conflict story', 'question-based framework', 'balanced perspective', 'reflective tone'],
        E'Founders, STOP following one-size-fits-all startup advice.\n\nThe fallout is subtle but real.\nPeople repeat quotes while their businesses quietly fail.\n\nI used to tell every founder to ''move fast and ship.''\nIt worked — until it didn''t.\n\nA recent founder copied the mantra — straight into payments.\nIt blew up in his face.\n\nI felt conflicted. I''d given him the wrong tool at the wrong time.\nIt stung to watch it happen.\n\nWe restarted the conversation and mapped his actual constraints.\nStage, regulation, and trust changed everything.\n\nHe said the thing everyone quotes. I asked different questions.\n\n• Blindly copying founders with different stages\n• Applying growth hacks where compliance matters\n• Prioritizing speed over user trust\n• Assuming scale fixes foundational flaws\n\nThe problem isn''t the advice — it''s the absence of context.\n\nAdvice has a stage and a condition.\nA quote without context can be dangerous.\n\nI told him exactly what to do instead:\n\n• Map the stage before you act\n• Ask: ''Will this break user trust?''\n• Prioritize safety when money is involved\n• Test in a low-risk sandbox first\n• Delay scale until retention is proven\n\nHe relaxed when we reframed the choice.\nRelief replaced panic in his voice.\n\nI''m not against bold moves.\nI''m against blind copying without context.\n\nFrameworks are tools, not commandments.\nUse them with judgement, not worship.\n\nIf you''re launching payments or finances:\n\nRe-evaluate that loud piece of advice.\nAsk these context questions before you act.\n\nWas this advice for a 10-person team or a 10,000-person company?\nWas it applied in a regulated environment?\n\nAlways add context to every quote you use.\n\nWise advice + wrong timing = expensive mistakes.'
    ),
    (
        'Personal Beliefs',
        'The Elephant In The Room',
        'Call out a widespread but rarely spoken industry problem. Use a personal story to show its real impact, expose root causes, and urge the community to fix it.',
        E'Opening Statement → Impact Description → Context Setting → Unexpected Turn → Initial Reaction → Transition to Core Story → Introduction to Key Points → Problem List → Reflection Bridge → Core Wisdom → Advice Introduction → Advice List → Emotional Response → Balanced Perspective → Universal Truth → Target Audience Call-Out → Call to Action → Reflection Questions → Final Guidance → Closing Statement',
        E'Opening Statement - Single line, personal action\nImpact Description - Two lines\nContext Setting - Two lines\nUnexpected Turn - Two lines\nInitial Reaction - Two lines\nTransition to Core Story - Two lines\nIntroduction to Key Points - One line',
        E'Problem List - 4-5 bullet points:\n• Problem 1\n• Problem 2\n• Problem 3\n• Problem 4\n\nReflection Bridge - One to two lines\n\nCore Wisdom - Two lines: Silence protects problem, transparency forces repair\n\nAdvice Introduction - One line\n\nAdvice List - 4-5 bullet points:\n• Concrete fix 1\n• Concrete fix 2\n• Concrete fix 3\n• Concrete fix 4\n• Concrete fix 5\n\nEmotional Response - Two lines\n\nBalanced Perspective - Two lines: Not blame, but design\n\nUniversal Truth - Two to three lines: Processes are promises\n\nTarget Audience Call-Out - One line\n\nCall to Action - Two lines: Audit and fix this week\n\nReflection Questions - Two lines: Vendor/partner timeline questions\n\nFinal Guidance - One line\n\nClosing Statement - One line: Silent problems become culture',
        E'End with truth about silent problems becoming company culture',
        ARRAY['single line breaks', 'short paragraphs (1-3 lines)', 'no hashtags', 'minimal emoji', 'calling out dysfunction', 'systems problem focus', 'transparency advocacy', 'concrete fixes', 'vendor relationships', 'process design', 'accountability ownership', 'community repair'],
        E'I called out the payment delays in public.\n\nThe reaction was immediate and messy.\nSome thanked me — others went silent.\n\nWe''d been waiting 90+ days for partner payouts.\nVendors started threatening to walk.\n\nA vendor posted our emails in a Slack channel.\nSuddenly, everyone saw the same problem.\n\nI felt embarrassed and furious at once.\nWe''d normalized a dysfunction.\n\nI began digging into the process with finance and ops.\nThe root looked worse than the symptom.\n\nHere''s what I found and what we must fix.\n\n• Manual invoice approvals creating multi-week delays\n• Weak SLAs with partners and vendors\n• Confused ownership across finance → ops → legal\n• No contingency lines for vendor survival\n\nIt''s not a cashflow problem alone — it''s a systems problem.\n\nSilence protects the problem. Transparency forces repair.\nCalling it out is the first step to fixing it.\n\nI recommended five concrete changes:\n\n• Publish SLA expectations with partners\n• Automate invoice routing & reminders\n• Create a vendor contingency fund (3–4 weeks)\n• Assign single-owner for payout cadence\n• Run monthly vendor health checks\n\nSome leaders resisted. Some implemented overnight.\nThe vendors who stayed were quietly grateful.\n\nThis isn''t about blame.\nIt''s about designing systems that honor people.\n\nIn business, processes are promises.\nWhen promises break, trust fractures faster than margins.\n\nIf you work with external vendors:\n\nAudit your payout flow this week.\nFix one choke point before Monday.\n\nHow long does a vendor wait to get paid in your system?\nWho owns that timeline?\n\nName the elephant. Then remove it.\n\nSilent problems become company culture — and that''s the real cost.'
    ),
    (
        'Personal Beliefs',
        'Here vs. Everywhere Else',
        'Contrast your experience in one community/platform vs. the noise elsewhere. Explain why your corner is better for growth and outline the values that make it so.',
        E'Opening Statement → Impact Description → Context Setting → Unexpected Turn → Initial Reaction → Transition to Core Story → Introduction to Key Points → Problem List → Reflection Bridge → Core Wisdom → Advice Introduction → Advice List → Emotional Response → Balanced Perspective → Universal Truth → Target Audience Call-Out → Call to Action → Reflection Questions → Final Guidance → Closing Statement',
        E'Opening Statement - Single line, personal action\nImpact Description - Two lines: Quality over quantity\nContext Setting - Two lines: Platform contrast\nUnexpected Turn - Two lines: Real DMs not likes\nInitial Reaction - Two lines\nTransition to Core Story - Two lines\nIntroduction to Key Points - One line',
        E'Problem List - 4-5 bullet points:\n• Platform A problem\n• Platform B problem\n• Reach vs relationship\n• Time and patience\n\nReflection Bridge - One to two lines: Community quality is choice\n\nCore Wisdom - Two lines: Presence > performance, Authenticity compounds\n\nAdvice Introduction - One line\n\nAdvice List - 4-5 bullet points:\n• Share work-in-progress\n• Respond to DMs meaningfully\n• One helpful thread weekly\n• Highlight process and metrics\n• Celebrate others publicly\n\nEmotional Response - Two lines: Felt seen not sold\n\nBalanced Perspective - Two lines: Virality vs sustained work\n\nUniversal Truth - Two to three lines: Predictability > spectacle\n\nTarget Audience Call-Out - One line\n\nCall to Action - Two lines: Teach not shout\n\nReflection Questions - Two lines: Applause vs clients\n\nFinal Guidance - One line\n\nClosing Statement - One line: Network as mirror',
        E'End with truth about network reflecting who you want to be',
        ARRAY['single line breaks', 'short paragraphs (1-3 lines)', 'no hashtags', 'minimal emoji', 'platform contrast', 'community over clout', 'authenticity focus', 'presence over performance', 'quality conversations', 'depth over reach', 'sustained work', 'reciprocal trust'],
        E'I stopped treating LinkedIn like everywhere else.\n\nIt changed my career trajectory.\nMy network quality went up, not my follower count.\n\nOn other platforms, noise is rewarded: flash over substance.\nHere, consistent help builds lasting relationships.\n\nAfter three months of showing up differently, people started DMing for work.\nNot likes — real asks.\n\nI was surprised by the tone shift.\nConversations became thoughtful, not performative.\n\nI stopped chasing virality and started showing process.\nThe community responded.\n\nWhy this place works — and how to join it.\n\n• Platform A rewards noise and quick dopamine\n• Platform B amplifies controversy for engagement\n• People mistake reach for relationship\n• Quality conversations require time and patience\n\nCommunity quality is a choice you make every post.\n\nPresence > performance.\nAuthenticity compounds — reach usually doesn''t.\n\nIf you want depth, start here:\n\n• Share work-in-progress, not just wins\n• Respond to DMs like they matter (because they do)\n• Post one helpful thread per week, not daily noise\n• Highlight process and metrics, not just outcomes\n• Celebrate others publicly to build reciprocal trust\n\nPeople thanked me for slowing down.\nThey said they felt seen, not sold.\n\nVirality can be useful.\nSustained work builds careers.\n\nOnline audiences reward predictability more than spectacle.\nShow up the same way, and the right people will notice.\n\nIf you want meaningful work opportunities:\n\nStart one thread that teaches, not shouts.\nWatch who shows up to learn.\n\nAre you building for applause or clients?\nWhich would you rather have in 12 months?\n\nChoose community over clout.\n\nYour network is a mirror — make sure it reflects who you want to be.'
    ),
    (
        'Personal Beliefs',
        'A Contrarian Take On Why People Ignore You',
        'Confront a common problem: people not engaging with your work. Reveal the uncomfortable truth behind low attention and offer a direct, empathetic alternative.',
        E'Opening Statement → Impact Description → Context Setting → Unexpected Turn → Initial Reaction → Transition to Core Story → Introduction to Key Points → Problem List → Reflection Bridge → Core Wisdom → Advice Introduction → Advice List → Emotional Response → Balanced Perspective → Universal Truth → Target Audience Call-Out → Call to Action → Reflection Questions → Final Guidance → Closing Statement',
        E'Opening Statement - Single line, personal action\nImpact Description - Two lines: Polite wrong answers\nContext Setting - Two lines: Blame algorithms vs message\nUnexpected Turn - Two lines: 100 profiles pattern\nInitial Reaction - Two lines: Industry bad habits\nTransition to Core Story - Two lines: Experiment results\nIntroduction to Key Points - One line',
        E'Problem List - 4-5 bullet points:\n• Vague value propositions\n• Hero-post mentality\n• Over-optimization for SEO\n• Ignoring clarity\n\nReflection Bridge - One to two lines: Not cruel, unclear\n\nCore Wisdom - Two lines: Clarity beats charisma, Specificity beats cleverness\n\nAdvice Introduction - One line: Three changes\n\nAdvice List - 4-5 bullet points:\n• State WHO you help\n• Promise clear outcome with numbers\n• Add micro-example (before → after)\n• Make CTA frictionless\n• Repeat until it sticks\n\nEmotional Response - Two lines: Right people finally heard\n\nBalanced Perspective - Two lines: Skill not insult\n\nUniversal Truth - Two to three lines: Attention is currency, Clarity is exchange rate\n\nTarget Audience Call-Out - One line\n\nCall to Action - Two lines: Rewrite headline, post below\n\nReflection Questions - Two lines: Who exactly, what outcome\n\nFinal Guidance - One line: Be useful not mysterious\n\nClosing Statement - One line: Ignore mystery not noise',
        E'End with truth about ignoring mystery not noise',
        ARRAY['single line breaks', 'short paragraphs (1-3 lines)', 'no hashtags', 'minimal emoji', 'uncomfortable truth', 'clarity advocacy', 'specificity focus', 'contrarian positioning', 'empathetic directness', 'messaging diagnosis', 'value proposition', 'frictionless CTA'],
        E'I asked a room of founders why people ignore their posts.\n\nThe answers were polite and wrong.\nThe real reason stung.\n\nThey blamed algorithms, timing, and luck.\nI blamed their message.\n\nAfter reading 100 profiles and DMs, a pattern emerged.\nMost messaging was vague and forgettable.\n\nI felt frustrated — not at them, but at the industry''s bad habits.\nWe taught people to chase virality, not clarity.\n\nSo I experimented: one week of specific, helpful posts.\nResponses tripled.\n\nHere''s the crass truth and what to do about it.\n\n• Vague value propositions (no audience, no outcome)\n• Hero-post mentality (showing wins, not teaching)\n• Over-optimization for SEO and not humans\n• Ignoring the simplest mental shortcut: clarity\n\nPeople don''t ignore you because they''re cruel. They ignore you because you''re unclear.\n\nClarity beats charisma.\nSpecificity beats cleverness.\n\nFix it with three changes:\n\n• State WHO you help in one sentence\n• Promise a clear outcome with numbers when possible\n• Add one micro-example (before → after)\n• Make the CTA frictionless (comment, DM, or sign-up)\n• Repeat the message until it sticks\n\nOnce they clarified, founders finally heard from the right people.\nRelief replaced desperate posting.\n\nThis isn''t an insult — it''s a skill.\nNobody teaches clarity by default.\n\nAttention is currency.\nClarity is the exchange rate.\n\nIf you wonder why no one replies:\n\nRewrite your headline to name one person and one result.\nPost it below — I''ll tell you if it''s clear.\n\nWho exactly are you talking to?\nWhat measurable outcome do you promise?\n\nStop being mysterious. Be useful.\n\nPeople don''t ignore noise — they ignore mystery.'
    ),
    (
        'Personal Beliefs',
        'Is It Time To Step Back?',
        'Share a personal story where the best move wasn''t to keep pushing — it was to pause. Challenge the "never give up" mindset and show why rest and realignment can be the bravest action.',
        E'Opening Statement → Impact Description → Context Setting → Unexpected Turn → Initial Reaction → Transition to Core Story → Introduction to Key Points → Problem List → Reflection Bridge → Core Wisdom → Advice Introduction → Advice List → Emotional Response → Balanced Perspective → Universal Truth → Target Audience Call-Out → Call to Action → Reflection Questions → Final Guidance → Closing Statement',
        E'Opening Statement - Single line, personal action\nImpact Description - Two lines: Not weakness, clarity\nContext Setting - Two lines: Pitch rejection\nUnexpected Turn - Two lines: Called for perspective not money\nInitial Reaction - Two lines\nTransition to Core Story - Two lines: 1:1 opening up\nIntroduction to Key Points - One line',
        E'Problem List - 4-5 bullet points:\n• Exhaustion\n• Co-founders leaving\n• Running out of money\n• Forgotten family/kids\n\nReflection Bridge - One to two lines: Truth rarely said aloud\n\nCore Wisdom - Two lines: Bravest thing is knowing when to step back\n\nAdvice Introduction - One line\n\nAdvice List - 4-5 bullet points:\n• Go be a dad/parent\n• Spend time with kids\n• Stop worrying about fundraising\n• Remember there''s more to life\n• Put mental health first\n\nEmotional Response - Two lines: "I''ve forgotten how to do that"\n\nBalanced Perspective - Two lines: Not quit dreams, pause and recalibrate\n\nUniversal Truth - Two to three lines: Life isn''t just companies, being present and loved\n\nTarget Audience Call-Out - One line\n\nCall to Action - Two lines: Zoom out, audit energy not runway\n\nReflection Questions - Two lines: Push forward or step back\n\nFinal Guidance - One line: Listen to gut\n\nClosing Statement - One line: You might already know',
        E'End with truth about already knowing the answer',
        ARRAY['single line breaks', 'short paragraphs (1-3 lines)', 'no hashtags', 'minimal emoji', 'triple line breaks for drama', 'pause over push', 'mental health priority', 'family focus', 'vulnerable story', 'bravery redefined', 'energy audit', 'life beyond business', 'gut instinct'],
        E'I told another founder to quit his startup.\n\nWhat happened next hit me. Hard.\nIt wasn''t weakness — it was clarity.\n\nHe came to pitch his company to our fund.\nWe rejected him.\n\nBut then, he booked a call with me on Hubble.\nHe didn''t want money — he wanted perspective.\n\nIt caught me off-guard at first.\nI didn''t know what to expect.\n\nWhen we started talking 1:1, he opened up.\nHe was done pretending everything was fine.\n\nHe told me:\n\n• He was exhausted\n• His co-founders were leaving\n• They were running out of money\n• He had forgotten to show up for his kids\n\nWhen I heard all this, I realized a truth that''s rarely said aloud:\n\nSometimes the bravest thing isn''t to keep pushing.\nIt''s knowing when to step back.\n\nI told him:\n\n• Go be a dad\n• Spend time with your kids\n• Stop worrying about fundraising\n• Remember there''s more to life\n• Put your mental health first\n\nHe just looked at me and said:\n"I''ve forgotten how to do that."\n\nLook, I''m not saying quit on your dreams.\nBut know when to pause and recalibrate.\n\nLife isn''t just about building companies.\nIt''s about being present, being loved, and having fun.\n\nIf you''re an early-stage founder:\n\nTake a second to zoom out.\nAudit your energy, not just your runway.\n\nIs it time to push forward?\nOr, is it time to step back?\n\nListen to your gut.\n\nYou might already know the answer.'
    ),
    
-- Op-Eds Templates (5 templates)
    (
        'Op-Eds',
        'The Step Before The First Step',
        'Debunk the popular "first step" in any process. Show why jumping to the obvious tactic fails and outline the foundational prerequisites you must establish first for real success.',
        E'Opening Challenge → Initial Process List → Reality Transition → Problem Sequence → Core Metaphor → Reality Check → Prerequisites Introduction → Critical Components → Consequence Statement → Problem Elaboration → Audience Engagement → Solution Introduction → Core Principles → Correct Approach Introduction → Solution Steps → Timing Rule → Payoff Setup → Payoff Statement → P.S. Hook → Final Punch',
        E'Opening Challenge - 1 line, 8–12 words\nInitial Process List - 4 items, 1–3 words each\nReality Transition - 1 line, 5–7 words\nProblem Sequence - 3 items, 2–4 words each\nCore Metaphor - 1 line, 8–12 words\nReality Check - 1–2 lines, 10–15 words',
        E'Prerequisites Introduction - 1 line, 2–4 words\n\nCritical Components - 4 items, 4–8 words each:\n• Component 1\n• Component 2\n• Component 3\n• Component 4\n\nConsequence Statement - 1–2 lines, 10–15 words\n\nProblem Elaboration - 2 lines, 12–15 words each\n\nAudience Engagement - 1 line, 8–12 words\n\nSolution Introduction - 1 line, 5–7 words\n\nCore Principles - 3 items, 6–8 words each\n\nCorrect Approach Introduction - 1 line, 1–2 words\n\nSolution Steps - 3 items, 2–4 words each\n\nTiming Rule - 1–2 lines, 15–20 words\n\nPayoff Setup - 1 line, 5–7 words\nPayoff Statement - 1 line, 5–7 words\nP.S. Hook - 1 line, 3–5 words\nFinal Punch - 1 line, 3–5 words',
        E'End with practical swing toward action and revenue focus',
        ARRAY['short lists with plus signs', 'tight visceral metaphors', 'practical action swing', 'prerequisites focus', 'compounding interest metaphor', 'direct response emphasis', 'evidence-driven', 'contrarian framework', 'foundational thinking', 'anti-obvious tactics', 'buyer journey focus', 'revenue over vanity'],
        E'I used to think SEO was the first thing you did:\n\n• Keyword research\n• Content calendar\n• Hit publish\n• Repeat\n\nBut here''s what actually happened:\n\n• I''d rank\n• I''d get traffic\n• And then...nothing\n\nSEO is the compounding interest of marketing.\n\nBut if you''ve ever been broke, you know you can''t compound zero.\n\nIf you haven''t nailed:\n\n• your marketing offer (what do they want before my software?)\n• your positioning (why you, not them)\n• your messaging (clarity beats creativity)\n• and your buyer journey (from curiosity → purchase)\n\n...then SEO is just content with a longer deadline.\n\nYou''ll spend months writing posts for people who were never going to buy anyway.\nWhich, if you''re senior enough, know is a road to ruin.\n\nRaise your hand if you''ve heard ''why isn''t traffic converting?''\n\nHere''s what I tell clients now:\n\nDon''t optimize a funnel that doesn''t convert.\nDon''t publish for searchers you don''t understand.\nDon''t chase traffic when you haven''t proven traction.\n\nStart with:\n\n• Direct response.\n• Relationship selling.\n• Mid-funnel experiments (almost nobody runs these—do them first)\n\nThen — and only then — should you turn on the compound-interest machine that is SEO.\n\nBecause when you do get it right?\n\nSEO is like opening the floodgates.\n\nP.S. I still love SEO...\n\nbut I love revenue more.'
    ),
    (
        'Op-Eds',
        'The Hidden Cost Of A Broken Promise',
        'Explain how tiny, repeated product failures erode user trust over time. Show the invisible damage metrics don''t capture, and outline the discipline needed to rebuild credibility.',
        E'Opening Scene → Situation Background → Current State Description → Core Problem Statement → Problem Definition → Impact Description → Key Insight → Problem Escalation → Problem Summary → Universal Principle → Essential Truth → Solution Framework → Critical Practice → Opportunity Statement → Success Outcome → Closing Principle',
        E'Opening Scene - Personal anecdote hook\nSituation Background - Problem introduction\nCurrent State Description - Symptom list\nCore Problem Statement - Single line impact\nProblem Definition - Broad context\nImpact Description - Hidden effects',
        E'Key Insight - Universal truth: Once belief slips, capability doesn''t win it back\n\nProblem Escalation - Cyclical impact\n\nProblem Summary - Naming the cost: Compounding loss of confidence\n\nUniversal Principle - Core truth: Shaping expectation with every failure\n\nEssential Truth - Simple statement\n\nSolution Framework - Success pattern:\n• Ship carefully\n• Instrument for confidence\n• Treat first use as reputation test\n\nCritical Practice - Key action: Fix smallest failures fast\n\nOpportunity Statement - Market context\n\nSuccess Outcome - Future state: Product people defend at work\n\nClosing Principle - Final impact: Trust compounds into lock-in',
        E'End with business upside (trust compounds into lock-in)',
        ARRAY['vivid symptoms', 'short sentences for hidden effects', 'trust as central metric', 'invisible damage focus', 'compounding loss', 'belief erosion', 'reliability over features', 'first-use reputation', 'confidence instrumentation', 'lock-in outcome', 'scar tissue metaphor', 'expectation shaping'],
        E'I just got off the phone with a founder. It was an early Sunday morning call, and they were distraught.\n\nThe company launched a breakout AI feature. That one worked. Every new release since? Nothing''s sticking.\n\nThe team is moving fast. They add features. Adoption is flat. Momentum fades.\n\nNo one''s saying it out loud, but the trust is gone.\n\nThis is how AI features fail. Because they teach the user a quiet lesson: don''t rely on this.\n\nThe damage isn''t logged. It doesn''t show in dashboards. It shows in slow engagement and quick abandonment.\n\nOnce belief slips, no amount of capability wins it back.\n\nTeams ship fixes, release demos, pitch harder — but scar tissue remains. Users stop expecting anything.\n\nThis is the hidden cost of broken product promises: compounding loss of confidence.\n\nYou''re shaping expectation whether you know it or not. Every failure subtracts belief.\n\nThat''s the real game.\n\nThe teams that win build trust: ship carefully, instrument for confidence, and treat first use as a reputation test.\n\nAnd they fix the smallest failures fast — because one broken output can define the relationship.\n\nVery few teams do this. Most chase the next ''feature'' instead of reliability.\n\nIf you get this right, you become the product people defend at work. You become hard to replace.\n\nTrust compounds. When it does, it turns belief into lock-in.'
    ),
    (
        'Op-Eds',
        'What An Expert Taught Me (& What To Unlearn)',
        'Structure a post around a game-changing insight from an industry leader. Use it to dismantle outdated dogma and lay out a new, contrarian framework readers can apply.',
        E'Opening Claim → Context Setup → The Expert Moment → What To Unlearn → Why It''s Wrong → The New Framework → How I Applied It → Result Snapshot → What To Teach Your Team → Audience Prompt → Final Directive',
        E'Opening Claim - 1 line, attention-getter\nContext Setup - 1–2 lines\nThe Expert Moment - 2 lines: Expert quote\nWhat To Unlearn - 3 items, 3–6 words each\nWhy It''s Wrong - 2 lines',
        E'The New Framework - 3 principles, 6–8 words each:\n• Principle 1\n• Principle 2\n• Principle 3\n\nHow I Applied It - 3 steps, 2–4 words each:\n• Step 1\n• Step 2\n• Step 3\n\nResult Snapshot - 1–2 lines with metric\n\nWhat To Teach Your Team - 2 lines\n\nAudience Prompt - 1 line: Who taught you something\n\nFinal Directive - 1 line: Trade clever fixes for durable systems',
        E'End with prompt for readers to share their mentor moments',
        ARRAY['short declarative bullets', 'unlearn points', 'concrete metric for credibility', 'mentor moment prompt', 'expert insight', 'contrarian framework', 'retention focus', 'durable design', 'lifetime value', 'repeatable behavior', 'anti-vanity metrics', 'retention proof'],
        E'An expert told me to stop doing the thing I thought was essential.\n\nI''d spent years optimizing funnels, AB-testing headlines, and chasing small lifts. He asked one question that stopped me cold.\n\nHe said: ''Stop optimizing noise. Design for repeatable behavior.''\nIt felt obvious and then revolutionary.\n\nWhat To Unlearn:\n• Stop treating uplift as long-term success\n• Stop celebrating vanity metric wins\n• Stop optimizing without retention proof\n\nThese habits produce short spikes, not durable growth. You optimize the wrong lever and scale a weak foundation.\n\nThe New Framework:\n• Design for retentive user flows first.\n• Build experiments that prove repeat usage.\n• Make onboarding your single KPI before scale.\n\nHow I Applied It:\n• Rewired onboarding flows\n• Measured day-7 retention\n• Iterated on key micro-moments\n\nWithin 6 weeks, retention rose 28% and activation doubled. The business stopped leaking users.\n\nUnlearn short-term hacks. Teach durable design. Reward fixes that increase lifetime value.\n\nWho taught you something that made you unlearn?\n\nTrade clever fixes for durable systems.'
    ),
    (
        'Op-Eds',
        'The Red Flag You Can''t Ignore',
        'Share a cautionary tale about a major red-flag you encountered (e.g., a toxic founder-investor dynamic). Explain the signs, the costs of ignoring them, and the decisive action you recommend.',
        E'Opening Hook → Situation Setup → Red Flag Moment → Immediate Impact → Root Cause → Consequences → Hard Decision → Lesson Learned → What To Watch For → Action Steps → Founder/Investor Call-Out → Closing Moral',
        E'Opening Hook - 1 line, punchy\nSituation Setup - 2 lines\nRed Flag Moment - 1 line\nImmediate Impact - 2 lines: Room went cold\nRoot Cause - 2 lines: Culture of shortcuts\nConsequences - 3 bullet points',
        E'Hard Decision - 2 lines: Paused funding, ran forensic review\n\nLesson Learned - 1–2 lines: Address red flags early\n\nWhat To Watch For - 4 items, short phrases:\n• Overly polished reports\n• Reluctance to answer questions\n• Pressure to close quickly\n• Creative accounting language\n\nAction Steps - 3 items:\n• Insist on open books.\n• Escalate to counsel early.\n• Pause decisions until clarity exists.\n\nFounder/Investor Call-Out - 1 line\n\nClosing Moral - 1 line: Red flags are signals, not suggestions',
        E'End with forceful moral about acting on red flags',
        ARRAY['anecdote opening', 'enumerate red flags', 'non-negotiable action steps', 'concise moral', 'cautionary tale', 'trust erosion', 'forensic review', 'narrative inflation', 'creative accounting', 'legal exposure', 'open books', 'decisive action'],
        E'I ignored a red flag — and it cost us more than money.\n\nIt started with one offhand comment in a board meeting. We brushed it off as stress.\n\nThe founder asked us to "move funds around" to hit numbers.\n\nI felt the room go cold. People who once nodded started asking hard questions. Trust shifted.\n\nIt wasn''t a single act. It was a culture of short-cuts and narrative inflation.\n\n• Revenue numbers that smelled too tidy\n• Key hires leaving quietly\n• Legal exposure bubbling under the surface\n\nWe paused funding. We ran a forensic review. It was painful — but necessary.\n\nAddress red flags early. Dismissal compounds risk into crisis.\n\nWhat To Watch For:\n• Overly polished reports without depth\n• Reluctance to answer operational questions\n• Pressure to ''close quickly'' with no audit trail\n• Frequent ''creative'' accounting language\n\nAction Steps:\n• Insist on open books.\n• Escalate to counsel early.\n• Pause decisions until clarity exists.\n\nIf you''re a founder: don''t hide issues behind stories.\n\nRed flags are signals, not suggestions — act.'
    ),
    (
        'Op-Eds',
        'An Unavoidable Change Is Coming',
        'Sound the alarm about an industry disruption that makes old playbooks obsolete. Expose the hidden threat, argue why incumbents are vulnerable, and present practical next steps readers should take now.',
        E'Opening Alarm → Threat Snapshot → Hidden Mechanic → Why It Matters → Evidence Sequence → Incumbent Weakness → What Will Break → What To Build Instead → Early Adopter Moves → Risk/Reward Statement → Call to Action → Final Urgency',
        E'Opening Alarm - 1 line, urgent\nThreat Snapshot - 2 lines: Slow and inevitable\nHidden Mechanic - 1 line\nWhy It Matters - 2 lines: Attention model shifting\nEvidence Sequence - 3 items, short\nIncumbent Weakness - 2 lines',
        E'What Will Break - 3 bullet points:\n• Long-form SEO-dependent acquisition\n• Ad-dependent growth funnels\n• One-size-fits-all onboarding\n\nWhat To Build Instead - 3 items, 3–6 words each:\n• Micro-affinity hooks (community-first)\n• Product-led discovery loops\n• Intent signal conversion paths\n\nEarly Adopter Moves - 3 steps:\n• Instrument micro-behaviors now.\n• Run small community experiments.\n• Tie every signal to value delivery.\n\nRisk/Reward Statement - 1–2 lines\n\nCall to Action - 1 line: Audit funnel for fragility\n\nFinal Urgency - 1 line: Start building today',
        E'End with urgent call to start building for disruption today',
        ARRAY['short evidence bullets', 'build urgency', 'clear tactical next steps', 'instrumentation focus', 'community experiments', 'disruption alarm', 'attention model shift', 'incumbent vulnerability', 'micro-affinity', 'intent signals', 'network effects', 'early mover advantage'],
        E'An unavoidable change is coming to product discovery.\n\nIt won''t be flashy. It will be slow and inevitable.\nOld heuristics will fail faster than teams can adapt.\n\nIt''s not the tech — it''s the attention model shifting underneath us.\n\nCompanies that monetize attention will win. Those that monetize clicks will struggle.\nYour acquisition tactics won''t translate.\n\nEvidence:\n• Changing attention (short-form → micro-affinity)\n• New discovery (algorithmic scaffolds, not search)\n• Monetization gap (engagement ≠ revenue)\n\nLarge players rest on distribution and assumptions about user intent.\nAssumptions are brittle under new attention dynamics.\n\nWhat Will Break:\n• Long-form SEO-dependent acquisition\n• Ad-dependent growth funnels with high CAC\n• One-size-fits-all onboarding flows\n\nWhat To Build Instead:\n• Micro-affinity hooks (community-first)\n• Product-led discovery loops (network effects)\n• Conversion paths tied to intent signals\n\nEarly Adopter Moves:\n• Instrument micro-behaviors now.\n• Run small community experiments.\n• Tie every signal to value delivery.\n\nAct early and you capture the new distribution. Move late and you subsidize incumbents'' transition.\n\nAudit one funnel this week for attention fragility.\n\nThis shift is happening quietly. Start building for it today.'
    ),
    
-- Build in Public Templates (5 templates)
    (
        'Build in Public',
        'How To Succeed Without A Grand Vision',
        'Share a journey from self-doubt to meaningful progress by showing how small, consistent actions built momentum and confidence. Perfect for founders who grew by doing, not by dreaming.',
        E'Opening Confession → Initial Reality → Humble Admission Series → Basic Motivation → Internal Conflict → Vulnerable Moment → Progress Beginning → Growth Progression Series → Key Realization → Core Wisdom → Action-Result Connection → Universal Truth → Final Insight → Visual Element',
        E'Opening Confession - 15–20 words\nInitial Reality - 15–20 words\nHumble Admission Series - 2–3 short statements\nBasic Motivation - 15–20 words\nInternal Conflict - 15–20 words\nVulnerable Moment - 5–10 words',
        E'Progress Beginning - 15–20 words\n\nGrowth Progression Series - 3–4 statements:\n"When we hit X customers, we felt Y."\n"Then X customers felt possible."\n"Then X customers felt like momentum."\n\nKey Realization - 10–15 words\n\nCore Wisdom - 10–15 words: Ambition follows evidence\n\nAction-Result Connection - 10–15 words\n\nUniversal Truth - 15–20 words: Don''t need vision to start, need repeatable system\n\nFinal Insight - 3–5 words: Vision comes later\n\nVisual Element: ✌️',
        E'End with simple truth that vision can come later',
        ARRAY['humble beginning', 'self-doubt vulnerability', 'small wins compound', 'evidence builds belief', 'no grand vision needed', 'weekly shipping', 'customer milestones', 'confidence from results', 'repeatable system', 'doing over dreaming', 'momentum narrative', 'anti-ambition pressure'],
        E'When I started in 2019, I had zero ambition, and I felt ashamed about it…\n\nMy only goal then was to get a stable paycheck so I could stop borrowing money from friends.\n\nI didn''t want to change the world.\nI didn''t have a 10-year master plan.\n\nI simply wanted something that paid the rent and let me learn while doing it.\n\nBut seeing founders with big visions made me compare and feel small…\n\nI thought I''d never matter.\n\nThen I started shipping one small thing every week. Tiny wins added up.\n\nAnd when we hit 10 customers, we felt validated.\nThen 100 customers felt possible.\nThen 1,000 customers felt like momentum.\n\nMy confidence grew because results accumulated, not because my vision did.\n\nAmbition follows evidence. Proof builds belief.\n\nDo one measurable thing weekly — the compound effect is real.\n\nYou don''t need a grand vision to start. You need a system you can repeat.\n\nVision can come later.\n\n✌️'
    ),
    (
        'Build in Public',
        'How To Win When The Odds Are Stacked Against You',
        'Tell an "against-all-odds" story with a tight framework and timeline: obstacles, tactical playbook, dates, and outcome. Great for fundraising or product-launch stories.',
        E'Headline → Context Setting → Challenge List → Business Position → Stakes → Framework Introduction → Strategy Breakdown → Timeline Header → Timeline Details → Result Summary → Key Insight',
        E'Headline - 15–20 words: Framework name and outcome\nContext Setting - 10–15 words: Worst possible timing\nChallenge List - 4–6 bullet points\nBusiness Position - 15–20 words\nStakes - 25–30 words: Real pressure',
        E'Framework Introduction - 10–15 words\n\nStrategy Breakdown - 3–4 steps:\n4: Practice with lower-tier\n1: Pitch top-tier directly\n2: Revisit second-tier sharpened\n3: Close with tier-3 if needed\n\nTimeline Header - 5–10 words\n\nTimeline Details - 4–6 points:\nDate 1: Status\nDate 2: Status\nDate 3: Status\nDate 4: Outcome\n\nResult Summary - 2 lines: Momentum built quickly\n\nKey Insight - 2 lines: Practice first, then aim for moon',
        E'End with insight about practicing before aiming high',
        ARRAY['against-all-odds narrative', 'tight timeline', 'dated milestones', 'tactical framework', 'fundraising story', 'practice-first strategy', 'tiered approach', 'momentum building', 'student founder', 'worst timing', 'real stakes', 'executable playbook'],
        E'We raised $2M+ from Lightspeed before incorporation using our ''4-1-2-3'' fundraising strategy:\n\nIt was December 2022 — possibly the worst month to start fundraising.\n\n• VCs were largely unresponsive\n• I had no legal entity — only a prototype\n• I was still attending UChicago classes\n• Product-market fit was nascent\n• The macro environment was tightening quickly\n\nWe were building an AI-services product for SMBs — the opposite of what VCs traditionally love.\n\nStudent loans and rent were real. We gave ourselves 20 days to raise or we''d pivot to job hunting instead of entrepreneurship.\n\nHere''s the ''4-1-2-3'' framework that actually worked for us:\n\n4: Practice with four lower-tier VCs to refine story and objections.\n1: Pitch top-tier (ambitious) funds directly.\n2: Revisit second-tier funds with a sharpened deck.\n3: Close with tier-3 if needed for speed.\n\nHow we executed:\n\nDec 25–31: Silence; no replies.\nJan 4: First serious conversations started.\nJan 14: Lightspeed signaled intent.\nJan 17: Term sheet arrived — we incorporated afterwards.\n\nMomentum built quickly once a lead emerged.\nWe closed the round in under 3 weeks.\n\nMost founders aim for the top first.\nPractice first; then aim for the moon.'
    ),
    (
        'Build in Public',
        'The Grind That Forges Belief',
        'Detail a grueling period (e.g., fundraising pitch rejections, harsh product feedback) and map the step-by-step process you used to turn feedback into conviction. Show how the struggle created durable belief.',
        E'Opening Hook → Situation Context → Feedback Snapshot → Immediate Reaction → Step 1 (Diagnose) → Step 2 (Small Experiments) → Step 3 (Rebuild Playbook) → Step 4 (Iterate Publicly) → Turning Point → Outcome Snapshot → Core Lesson',
        E'Opening Hook - 1 line: Rejection count\nSituation Context - 2 lines\nFeedback Snapshot - 3–4 bullets\nImmediate Reaction - 2 lines: Data not destiny',
        E'Step 1 - Diagnose the Critiques:\n• Catalog every feedback piece\n• Group by theme and frequency\n\nStep 2 - Small Experiments:\n• Run 3 rapid experiments\n• Measurable within 7 days\n\nStep 3 - Rebuild Playbook:\n• Update positioning from interviews\n• Change pitch to reflect outcomes\n\nStep 4 - Iterate Publicly:\n• Share small wins with investors\n• Use public fixes as momentum evidence\n\nTurning Point - 2 lines: Narrative shifted after 6 weeks\n\nOutcome Snapshot - 1–2 lines: Closed support, early customers\n\nCore Lesson - 2 lines: Feedback as experiment, grind forges belief through proof',
        E'End with lesson about feedback as fuel and repeatable proof',
        ARRAY['rejection narrative', '14 times in one month', 'feedback as data', 'rapid 7-day experiments', 'validated outcomes', 'public iteration', 'small wins sharing', 'narrative shift', 'micro-experiments', 'conviction building', 'grueling period', 'durable belief'],
        E'I got told ''this will never work'' — 14 times in one month.\n\nIt was during a critical fundraising window. Every investor had the same blunt feedback. Morale dropped.\n\n• Product lacks differentiation\n• GTM is unclear\n• Team execution looks thin\n\nI could have folded. Instead, we treated the feedback like data, not destiny.\n\nStep 1 - Diagnose the Critiques\n• Catalog every piece of feedback.\n• Group by theme and frequency.\n\nStep 2 - Small Experiments\n• Run 3 rapid experiments to validate or disprove critiques.\n• Each experiment must be measurable within 7 days.\n\nStep 3 - Rebuild Playbook\n• Update positioning based on user interviews.\n• Change the pitch to reflect validated outcomes.\n\nStep 4 - Iterate Publicly\n• Share small wins with investors and community.\n• Use public fixes as evidence of momentum.\n\nAfter 6 weeks of relentless micro-experiments, the narrative shifted.\nInvestors began asking different questions.\n\nWe closed support and had early customers commit. Confidence replaced doubt.\n\nHard feedback becomes fuel when you treat it like an experiment.\nThe grind forges belief because it forces repeatable proof.'
    ),
    (
        'Build in Public',
        'Why A ''Best Practice'' Is Actually A Trap',
        'Call out an accepted "best practice" (e.g., weekly meetings, conventional onboarding) and explain with a personal example why it can trap teams. Offer a counterintuitive alternative that worked for you.',
        E'Opening Claim → Context Setting → Symptoms → Personal Example → Why It''s a Trap → Counter-Approach → Result → Takeaway',
        E'Opening Claim - 1 line: Best practice killed momentum\nContext Setting - 2 lines\nSymptoms - 3 bullets\nPersonal Example - 2 lines: Alternative and outcome\nWhy It''s a Trap - 2 lines: Context and rituals',
        E'Counter-Approach - 3 points:\n• Time-box decisions to 24 hours.\n• Replace recurring meetings with async docs.\n• Reserve live syncs for decisions only.\n\nResult - 2 lines with metric: 30% increase in deep work\n\nTakeaway - 1–2 lines: Defaults not doctrines, test before adopt',
        E'End with principle to test before adopting best practices',
        ARRAY['best practice trap', 'weekly meetings critique', 'async accountability', 'deep focus windows', 'activity vs progress', 'counterintuitive alternative', 'context-dependent', 'rituals not tools', 'decision velocity', 'delivery predictability', 'productive friction', 'test before adopt'],
        E'Weekly all-hands? That ''best practice'' nearly killed our momentum.\n\nFor years we ran 90-minute all-hands every Monday. It felt productive. It wasn''t.\n\n• Meetings ate deep focus windows\n• Decisions were deferred to ''next Monday''\n• People confused activity for progress\n\nWe replaced it with a 10-minute async recap and a 1-hour monthly sync. Output jumped the very next week.\n\nBest practices assume context and scale that you may not have.\nThey become rituals, not tools.\n\nCounter-Approach:\n• Time-box decisions to 24 hours.\n• Replace recurring meetings with async accountability docs.\n• Reserve live syncs for decision-heavy discussions only.\n\nAfter the change: deep work hours increased 30% and delivery predictability improved.\n\nBest practices are defaults, not doctrines. Test before you adopt.'
    ),
    (
        'Build in Public',
        'They Say It''s Too Expensive (But Here''s the Real Reason)',
        'Respond to the common customer objection "it''s too expensive" by revealing the underlying, often hidden, reason (e.g., unclear ROI, poor internal ownership). Help readers reframe objections and offer tactical ways to surface the real barrier.',
        E'Opening Objection → Surface Claim → Reality Probe → Common Hidden Reasons → Example Diagnosis → Reframe for Sales → Proof Point → Takeaway Line → Call to Action',
        E'Opening Objection - 1 line\nSurface Claim - 1–2 lines: Neat and comfortable explanation\nReality Probe - 2 lines: Real issue emerged\nCommon Hidden Reasons - 4 bullets\nExample Diagnosis - 2 lines: Champion left, deal died',
        E'Reframe for Sales - 3 tactics:\n• Confirm owner who will pay and measure\n• Define exact metric for spend justification\n• Offer low-friction pilot with success criteria\n\nProof Point - 1–2 lines: 60% conversion with owner and metric\n\nTakeaway Line - 1 line: Price is proxy, solve real problem\n\nCall to Action - 1 line: If stalls, ask who will run week-to-week',
        E'End with call to action about identifying ownership',
        ARRAY['objection handling', 'too expensive reframe', 'hidden reasons', 'unclear ROI', 'internal ownership', 'procurement politics', 'champion dependency', 'pilot success criteria', 'measurement definition', 'onboarding capacity', 'price as proxy', 'owner confirmation'],
        E'They told us our product was ''too expensive.''\n\nPrice was the explanation they gave. It was neat and comfortable.\n\nBut after calls, demos, and shadowing, the real issue emerged.\nIt wasn''t sticker shock.\n\nCommon Hidden Reasons:\n• No clear owner for the outcome inside the buyer org\n• Undefined ROI measurement criteria\n• Internal politics blocking procurement\n• Lack of onboarding capacity\n\nIn one enterprise, the champion left mid-trial. Procurement stalled. The deal died — not because of price, but because of ownership.\n\nReframe for Sales:\n• Confirm the owner who will pay and measure success.\n• Define the exact metric the buyer will use to justify spend.\n• Offer a low-friction pilot with success criteria.\n\nWe converted 60% of pilots where an owner and a metric were agreed upfront.\n\nPrice is often a proxy. Solve the real problem — ownership, measurement, or capacity.\n\nIf sales stalls at ''too expensive,'' ask: who will run this week-to-week?'
    );

-- Update writing_templates table to add template_type field if not exists
DO $$ 
BEGIN
    IF NOT EXISTS (
        SELECT 1 FROM information_schema.columns 
        WHERE table_name = 'writing_templates' 
        AND column_name = 'template_type'
    ) THEN
        ALTER TABLE public.writing_templates 
        ADD COLUMN template_type TEXT DEFAULT 'user_defined' CHECK (template_type IN ('user_defined', 'preset'));
        
        -- Add index for template_type
        CREATE INDEX idx_writing_templates_type ON public.writing_templates(template_type);
    END IF;
END $$;

-- Add preset_template_id to writing_templates to track which preset was used
DO $$ 
BEGIN
    IF NOT EXISTS (
        SELECT 1 FROM information_schema.columns 
        WHERE table_name = 'writing_templates' 
        AND column_name = 'preset_template_id'
    ) THEN
        ALTER TABLE public.writing_templates 
        ADD COLUMN preset_template_id UUID REFERENCES public.preset_templates(id) ON DELETE SET NULL;
        
        -- Add index for preset_template_id
        CREATE INDEX idx_writing_templates_preset ON public.writing_templates(preset_template_id);
    END IF;
END $$;
